Squats...everyoneâs favorite exercise ð. The squat is a complex exercise and there are many common mistakes that are typically made. However, these are the two most common.
-
The most popular one is limited range of motion/half squats. Often times, it may actually feel as if you are squatting all the way down until you see a video and realize you arenât. If you do half reps, expect half the results.
-
Another common mistake is collapsing forward  and using too much back to lift the weight. This is usually in response to realizing you arenât going deep enough but rather than actually squatting deeper, you compensate by leaning forward and using your back. Your back should not be hurting during squats and your spine should stay neutral.
-
You should squat to at least parallel and possibly even slightly below. Proper, safe depth will depend on the person. I always recommend recording some of your sets to make sure your form is on point before you either get hurt, form bad habits, or just waste a bunch of time short changing yourself.
